Here's the information about React 19 Compiler and Vite configuration with `babel-plugin-react-compiler`:

## React Compiler Overview

React Compiler 1.0 is available today (released October 7, 2025). React Compiler is a build-time tool that optimizes your React app through automatic memoization.(no content)React Compiler can be installed across several build tools such as Babel, Vite, Metro, and Rsbuild.(no content)React Compiler is primarily a light Babel plugin wrapper around the core compiler, which was designed to be decoupled from Babel itself.

## Vite Configuration

Vite users can continue to use vite-plugin-react to enable the compiler, by adding it as a Babel plugin.

Here's the recommended configuration approach for Vite with `@vitejs/plugin-react`:

```javascript
// vite.config.js
import { defineConfig } from 'vite';
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react';

const compilerConfig = {
  target: '19' // can be '17' | '18' | '19', default is 19
};

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [
    react({
      babel: {
        plugins: [
          // make sure this is first in the plugins list
          ["babel-plugin-react-compiler", compilerConfig]
        ]
      }
    }),
  ],
});
```

React compiler is compatible with versions of React above 17 and is stable (v1 was released on Oct 7, 2025). It is available as a babel plugin, so to install it, install the babel-plugin-react-compiler package. For folks who are not yet on React 19 and are using versions 17 or 18, you need to install one more package named react-compiler-runtime@latest.

## Key Configuration Notes

React Compiler must run first in your Babel plugin pipeline. The compiler needs the original source information for proper analysis, so it must process your code before other transformations.(no content)React version configuration ensures the compiler generates code compatible with your React version. Target specifies which React version you're using (17, 18, or 19).

## Known Issues with TypeScript

The alternative way to configure react-compiler with Vitejs, which is to declare the Babel configuration separately, doesn't actually work in a TypeScript scenario.(no content)For the fix, it seems the babel config provided for react-router case works well with vite-plugin-react.

## Future Developments

The React team is also working with the oxc team to add support for the compiler. Once rolldown is officially released and supported in Vite and oxc support is added for React Compiler, they'll update the docs with information on how to migrate.(no content)Vite and Next.js users can choose the compiler enabled templates in create-vite and create-next-app.


